The key point is that there is a non‐integrable singularity at \(x=0\).  Split the integral as

\[
\int_{-1}^{2}\frac{dx}{x^3}
=\int_{-1}^{0}\frac{dx}{x^3} \;+\;\int_{0}^{2}\frac{dx}{x^3}\,.
\]

1)  On \((0,2]\):
\[
\int_{\varepsilon}^{2}\frac{dx}{x^3}
=\Big[-\tfrac1{2x^2}\Big]_{\;x=\varepsilon}^{\,2}
=-\frac1{2\cdot4}+\frac1{2\varepsilon^2}
=-\frac18+\frac1{2\varepsilon^2}
\;\longrightarrow\;+\infty
\quad(\varepsilon\to0^+).
\]

2)  On \([-1,0)\):
\[
\int_{-1}^{-\varepsilon}\frac{dx}{x^3}
=\Big[-\tfrac1{2x^2}\Big]_{x=-1}^{\,x=-\varepsilon}
=-\frac1{2\varepsilon^2}+\frac1{2}
\;\longrightarrow\;-\infty
\quad(\varepsilon\to0^+).
\]

Since each one‐sided integral blows up (one to \(+\infty\), the other to \(-\infty\)), the full improper integral does not converge.  

Remark:  If one were to form the Cauchy principal value
\[
\lim_{\varepsilon\to0^+}
\Big(\int_{-1}^{-\varepsilon}\frac{dx}{x^3}+\int_{\varepsilon}^{2}\frac{dx}{x^3}\Big)
\;=\;\frac{3}{8}\,,
\]
but the usual improper integral (in the sense of Lebesgue or of one‐sided Riemann limits) diverges.

The integral is improper at \(x=1\).  Write
\(\displaystyle\int_0^1\frac{dx}{1-x}
=\lim_{b\to1^-}\int_0^b\frac{dx}{1-x}
=\lim_{b\to1^-}\bigl[-\ln(1-x)\bigr]_0^b
=\lim_{b\to1^-}(-\ln(1-b))=+\infty.\)
Therefore the integral diverges.
